actually, that's a really good point.  Technically every endpoint should be using some kind of standard "subordinate override" variable name, otherwise we won't be able to support custom privilege registries in the future, which could have subordinate overrides at any level.

This doesn't appear done.....?  Technically any item can be overridden at any level, which would imply that the variable naming we've used is incorrect.  That needs to be discussed and accounted for in this patch.

I agree this will not fix stuff the way we want.

But to make it perfect, we need much robust solution.

A solution:
we need a list of all route path
Ex: 
"/redfish/v1/Systems/system/LogServices/EventLog/Actions/LogService.ClearLog/"
all rought has max 6 method GET, HEAD, PATCH, PUT, DELETE, POST. 

So we need to create six variables for them (the variable name is a little bit of a challenge because they have to be unique and easy to read)

Second, we need a keypair value with a single route with it @odata.type end value.
{{v1, ServiceRoot}, {Systems, ComputerSystemCollection}, {system, ComputerSystem}, {LogServices, LogServiceCollection}, {EventLog, LogService}}

in normal case just assign route path privilege.

Then for all SubordinateOverrides we map that path and assign proper privilege.

If we introduce a new route path or if the @odata.type end value gets updated, we still face the problem. (I mean, in that case, it is not robust)

is this too much work?

So you have 
putLogEntrySubOverComputerSystemLogServiceCollectionLogServiceLogEntryCollection
shouldn't instead you have 
putLogEntrySubOverComputerSystemLogServiceCollection
putLogEntrySubOverComputerSystemLogService
putLogEntrySubOverComputerSystemLogEntryCollection
putLogEntrySubOverComputerSystemLogEntry
? (1 variable for each SubOver)

I think it is completed.

Is there anything missing?

I don't see the paths that gunnar laid out implemented on all the endpoints.  As a practical example, grab the DMTF file and add a subordinate override to say, LogEntry, and see if this code still gives the right result.  It won't, and will keep the unoverridden permissions.

https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/45125/10..23/redfish-core/include/registries/privilege_registry.hpp

Hello, Ed checks this diff mainly LogEntry. here, you will find subordinate-override for each entry
-----------------------------
- ComputerSystem -> LogEntry
- ComputerSystem -> LogServiceCollection -> LogEntry
- ComputerSystem -> LogService -> LogEntry
- ComputerSystem -> LogEntryCollection -> LogEntry
- ComputerSystem -> LogServiceCollection -> LogService -> LogEntry
- ComputerSystem -> LogServiceCollection -> LogEntryCollection -> LogEntry
- etc..
Right, there are subordinate overrides, but did they get used?  No, because the calling code is pointing to privileges::getLogEntry, not the subordinate override for that particular node.

> 
> -------------------------------------------
> there is no GET and HEAD method so that's why we are using privileges::getLogEntry
> -------------------------------------------
> 

I forgot LogEntry already has a subordinate override already, hence why I think you're confused;  Lets say we added a subordinate override for SessionService, how would your code handle that?

I get what you mean. You want to create perfect code where we do not need to look back after making a subordinate override variable. Whenever any update happens, we override privilege and then do not need to update the code manually.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In the current code, the User needs to run scripts/parse_registries.py, and then after that, a new cost reference gets generated. So they need to use that (update the code manually).
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
But what you are asking might not be possible without making complicated changes.

Ex:  "Entity": "LogEntry" has two SubordinateOverrides "Targets" which means we need to have at least three references created. 1) for URL path which don't use SubordinateOverrides 2) first SubordinateOverrides 3) second SubordinateOverrides.
SubordinateOverrides definition: SubordinateOverrides lists a hierarchical representation for when to apply the override.

That means we need to support all. URL paths can support different hierarchical combinations.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What you are suggesting is also possible:
we need to create a cost ref variable for each URL(endpoint path), parse that URL ("@odata.id")  and then map it with an "Entity" of Redfish_1.1.0_PrivilegeRegistry.json. Then Check it has SubordinateOverrides or not. If yes, then map it "Targets," If the target map with URL path("@odata.id" parse and retrieve their "Entity"), it creates const ref for that privilege.

There are other complications too, but this is a basic idea.

> I get what you mean. You want to create perfect code where we do not need to look back after making a subordinate override variable. Whenever any update happens, we override privilege and then do not need to update the code manually.
> -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To be clear, I don't need perfect code, I need code that doesn't require maintainers to review every single override line item against the privileges to verify that the right overrides got set.  The whole point of the initial privilege registry implementation was because we found that we couldn't properly review that way, and lots of things were incorrect against the privilege registry.  Also, in the future, people want to override PrivilegeRegistry with their own custom ones (see the mailing list).  We need an implementation that gets us closer to that goal.  IMO, this takes us further away, and would need to be completely replaced to accomplish that goal.

> In the current code, the User needs to run scripts/parse_registries.py, and then after that, a new cost reference gets generated. So they need to use that (update the code manually).

Herein lies the problem.  In the future when people can override the privilege registry, or we have multiples, there's no way to have one registry have a subordinate override, and the other not.  That adds to the maintainance burden if we have to review this stuff every time there's a privilege registry change, or someone puts in their own custom one.

> -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
> But what you are asking might not be possible without making complicated changes.

Correct, this is why I didn't do it in the initial patchset, but to implement subordinate overrides, I think it's going to be necessary.

> 
> Ex:  "Entity": "LogEntry" has two SubordinateOverrides "Targets" which means we need to have at least three references created. 1) for URL path which don't use SubordinateOverrides 2) first SubordinateOverrides 3) second SubordinateOverrides.
> SubordinateOverrides definition: SubordinateOverrides lists a hierarchical representation for when to apply the override.
> 
> That means we need to support all. URL paths can support different hierarchical combinations.

Correct.

> ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
> What you are suggesting is also possible:
> we need to create a cost ref variable for each URL(endpoint path), parse that URL ("@odata.id")  and then map it with an "Entity" of Redfish_1.1.0_PrivilegeRegistry.json. Then Check it has SubordinateOverrides or not. If yes, then map it "Targets," If the target map with URL path("@odata.id" parse and retrieve their "Entity"), it creates const ref for that privilege.
> 
> There are other complications too, but this is a basic idea.

Yep, that sounds about right, and in line with what Gunnar was suggesting.
